<div class="blog-faq"><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>1. How can I verify a plastic surgeon's board certification online?</h3>
<p>You can verify a surgeon's certification through the official websites of the Association of Plastic Surgeons of India (APSI) or the Indian Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons (IAAPS). Simply search the surgeon's name in their member directory to confirm their active membership and certification status.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>2. What should I do if a surgeon refuses to show their credentials?</h3>
<p>A qualified surgeon should have no problem providing their credentials upon request. If a surgeon refuses to show their certifications, registration documents, or before-and-after photos, this is a major red flag. It is best to seek care from a different practitioner who is transparent about their qualifications.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>3. Are all cosmetic clinics required to be accredited?</h3>
<p>While accreditation requirements vary by region, it is always safest to choose an accredited facility. Accreditation ensures the facility meets established safety standards for equipment, staff qualifications, sterilization protocols, and emergency preparedness. Non-accredited facilities may not meet these essential safety benchmarks.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>4. Can a dermatologist perform plastic surgery?</h3>
<p>Some dermatologists perform minimally invasive cosmetic procedures like chemical peels, laser treatments, and injectable fillers. However, surgical procedures such as facelifts, liposuction, and rhinoplasty should only be performed by board-certified plastic surgeons who have completed the appropriate surgical residency training.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>5. How important are patient reviews when choosing a surgeon?</h3>
<p>Patient reviews provide valuable insight into the overall experience, including communication, bedside manner, facility quality, and post-operative care. While no single review tells the whole story, consistent patterns across multiple reviews are highly informative. Use reviews as one component of a broader verification process.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>6. What is the difference between a registered medical practitioner and a board-certified plastic surgeon?</h3>
<p>All doctors must be registered with the medical council to practice, but registration alone does not indicate specialization. Board certification in plastic surgery requires completion of an approved plastic surgery residency, passing rigorous examinations, and meeting ongoing education requirements. Always look for both registration and board certification.</p>
</div>

<div class="faq-item">
<h3>7. Should I be concerned if a surgeon offers very low prices?</h3>
<p>Unusually low prices can indicate the use of inexperienced staff, substandard equipment, unlicensed facilities, or cut corners on safety measures. While cost should be considered, it should never be the primary factor. Always prioritize safety, qualifications, and experience over price when choosing a surgeon.</p>
</div>

</div>
